mework was similar to that of nineteenth-century England, and many people experienced the patronizing attitudes inherent in these laws. New Brunswick Before the Equal Opportunity Program examines the observations and experiences of New Brunswick’s early social workers, who operated under this system, and illuminates how Premier Louis J. Robichaud’s Equal Opportunity program transformed the province’s social services. Authors Laurel Lewey, Louis J. Richard and Linda Turner, describe more than a century of social work history, including the work of the earliest Acadian social workers. They also address the fact that the federal government did not take responsibility for social welfare of the Mi’kmaq and Maliseet people, planning for assimilation instead. Clan structures continued to be relied on while subsisting upon inadequate relief provisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aChild welfarezNew BrunswickxHistory. 0aSocial servicezNew BrunswickxHistory. 0aSocial workerszNew BrunswickxHistory. 4aAcadian. 4aEqual Opportunity Program. 4aHistory. 4aInequality. 4aLouis Robichaud. 4aMaliseet. 4aMi'kmaq. 4aNew Brunswick. 4aSocial Work. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aRichard, Louis J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTurner, Linda M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751552240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487515522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487515522.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles